<m0>R-West Dade, District 37<ql>
Senate rank: 1<ql>
1995 rank: 2<ql>
<m1><styl>txt,1<ql>
<styl>indentr,2l,0,13l,7p1<ql>
<ep>
<m0>  Diaz-Balart, who has ambitions to become Senate president in 1998, earned his top ranking by virtue of his job as Ways and Means chairman. His biggest accomplishment: boosting education spending. But another GOP priority (--) no new taxes (--) meant cuts from other areas. To boost schools spending, the Senate tried to slash about $300 million from social services. Budget talks with the House reduced that to a $190 million cut. Too busy with the budget to handle much else, Diaz-Balart didn't deal with many other issues. But he did promote two bills that met with mixed results. He tried to pass a constitutional amendment to double the homestead exemption for fixed-income senior citizens. It never had a chance because House Speaker Peter Wallace blocked the plan, saying it hurt younger home owners by shifting the tax burden to them. Diaz-Balart had better luck (--) as he did in the budget (--) with education issues. His plan to let school districts use lottery money for school construction bonds cleared the Legislature without a hitch.<ql>
<m1><ql>
<styl>hed,1,18,1,fgn<ql>
<m0>DARYL JONES<ql>
<m1><ue5><m4>   LINE 1 IS 5.33 PICA(S) SHORT<m2><ql>
<m4>   TOTAL HEAD DEPTH IS .303 INCHES<m2><ql>
<ql>
<m1><styl>vs,1<styl>breakout<ql>
<m0>D-South Dade, District 40<ql>
Senate rank: 7<ql>
1995 rank: 5<ql>
<m1><styl>txt,1<ql>
<styl>indentr,2l,0,13l,7p1<ql>
<ep>
<m0>  It was a low-key session for a man designated to be Senate president (--) by Democrats not likely to gain control. He clung to the agendas of others: the governor's fight against tobacco and House members' bills. He half-heartedly pushed a plan to give a big pay raise to Dade commissioners as a favor to Rep. Luis Rojas. Jones liked the pay hike idea, but preferred it be done as Dade's charter requires: by countywide vote. After it cleared one panel, he refused to pursue it. He worked so school cops can make arrests beyond school borders. He fought to keep kids like Francisco Del Rey, who killed three people and maimed another with his speeding Corvette, from billing taxpayers for legal expenses when parents can pay. Both bills passed. Beyond a few eloquent speeches, most notably against school prayer, he seemed detached. A likely distraction was his role as fund-raiser for Democratic Senate races. An example of detachment: He was on the panel that produced a final budget agreement. But he skipped the last day of negotiations to be in Miami for President Clinton's visit.<ql>
<m1><ql>
<styl>hed,1,18,1,fgn<ql>
<m0>RON SILVER<ql>
<m1><ue5><m4>   LINE 1 IS 6.07 PICA(S) SHORT<m2><ql>
<m4>   TOTAL HEAD DEPTH IS .303 INCHES<m2><ql>
<ql>
<m1><styl>vs,1<styl>breakout<ql>
<m0>D-North Miami Beach, District 38<ql>
Senate rank: 8<ql>
1995 rank: 9<ql>
<m1><styl>txt,1<ql>
<styl>indentr,2l,0,13l,7p1<ql>
<ep>
<m0>  The chairman of Dade's 27-member delegation gave up on rallying the diverse and unwieldy group for consensus votes. Instead, he asked Dade, Broward and Palm Beach lawmakers to work together for tricounty clout. The most effective stand: defending South Florida education dollars. As usual, he focused on criminal justice issues. He worked on the Jimmy Ryce Act, which lets communities know when sexual predators are released in their midst (--) and to aid in the search for missing children. He worked to close a loophole allowing kids tried as adults to bill taxpayers for legal expenses, even when parents can pay. He was a vocal opponent of school prayer. He slashed $10 million from the lottery ad budget, a move some believed was a swipe at WPLG-Channel 10. The station runs lots of Lotto ads, and once ran an unflattering story on a gambling trip Silver took when he was supposed to be at a lawmakers' conference. Silver said the money would be better spent on education. He lost that one. Budget negotiators put the $10 million back.<ql>
