<m0>D-Pembroke Pines, District 32<ql>
1995 rank:    <ql>
<m1><styl>txt,1<ql>
<styl>indentr,2l,0,13l,7p1<ql>
<ep>
<m0>  If anyone qualifies as the conscience of the Senate, it's this liberal Democrat who represents Southwest Broward and Northwest Dade. Among hundreds of votes, one stands out: Forman was the only one of 160 lawmakers to vote against the $39.8 billion budget, protesting cuts to the poor and disabled. His principled protest carried a price: Forman was ostracized by the GOP majority. It was no coincidence he lost, over and over, on budget amendments and his bills. As usual, he carried a heavy workload. Advocates for the poor set up shop outside his office. It was not always a happy place. Despite his lone-wolf status, Forman scored victories: a fifth center for autistic people, tighter criteria for handicapped-parking passes, insurance coverage for longer maternity stays for mothers and babies and a study of the much-maligned transportation system for the poor and disabled. When many legislators seem motivated by a lust for power, money or both, Forman stands apart as a politician driven by a philosophy, not the trappings of office.<ql>
