<m0>ROBERTO CASAS<ql>
<m1><ue5><m4>   LINE 1 IS 3.55 PICA(S) SHORT<m2><ql>
<m4>   TOTAL HEAD DEPTH IS .303 INCHES<m2><ql>
<ql>
<m1><styl>vs,1<styl>breakout<ql>
<m0>R-Hialeah, District 39<ql>
1995 rank: **<ql>
<m1><styl>txt,1<ql>
<styl>indentr,2l,0,13l,7p1<ql>
<ep>
<m0>   If this longtime lawmaker is anything, it's predictable. Year after year he has the same agenda: Take care of Hialeah Park and create a special licensure path for a Dade-based group of Cuba- and Nicaragua-trained doctors. This year, he managed to do both. Helping out the thoroughbred track wasn't hard. As Regulated Industries chairman, he wields life-and-death power over parimutuel bills. Hanging in the balance was a sweeping packet of laws with everything from an expansion of betting at tracks to industry-wide tax breaks. Translation: a big-money, must-pass bill. Casas wouldn't sign off on it until it gave Hialeah Park an extra perk: the ability to take bets on races broadcast live from Calder Race Course. He got it. He also helped pass a plan to create a new licensing exam for a limited group of foreign-trained doctors. Another win came for his plan to give parents twice as long to sue when their infants are victims of medical mistakes. It went to the governor.<ql>
