<m0>ALBERTO GUTMAN<ql>
<m1><ue5><m4>   LINE 1 IS 2.73 PICA(S) SHORT<m2><ql>
<m4>   TOTAL HEAD DEPTH IS .303 INCHES<m2><ql>
<ql>
<m1><styl>vs,1<styl>breakout<ql>
<m0>R-Miami, District 34<ql>
1995 rank: ***<ql>
<m1><styl>txt,1<ql>
<styl>indentr,2l,0,13l,7p1<ql>
<ep>
<m0>  Once Health Care chairman, Gutman's power took a dive when he quit his post amid charges he used the position for financial gain. This was a reputation-mending year. He made hay of every high-profile case to hit South Florida: Two Plantation cops nearly lost health benefits after being severely injured. His bill forced cities to pay disabled cops' premiums. A tot died at the hands of a hit-and-run driver who confessed after a prosecution deadline. He did away with the statute of limitations. Four pilots were shot down by Cuban fighter jets. He pushed a Castro-condemning plan and the Cuban Freedom Act, a mirror image of the Helms-Burton law. Gutman had plenty of fodder for the district newsletter. Every issue passed. One not likely to make the newsletter: On the last day of session, he nearly amended to death a plan to regulate firms that buy life insurance policies from terminally ill patients. He gave up his killer amendments after sponsors retaliated by trying to amend to death one of <m0>his<m0>  bills: the one to protect cops' health benefits.<ql>
<m1><ql>
<styl>hed,1,18,1,fgn<ql>
<m0>BILL TURNER<ql>
<m1><ue5><m4>   LINE 1 IS 5.44 PICA(S) SHORT<m2><ql>
<m4>   TOTAL HEAD DEPTH IS .303 INCHES<m2><ql>
<ql>
