<m0>D-Miami Shores, District 36<ql>
1995 rank: **<ql>
<m1><styl>txt,1<ql>
<styl>indentr,2l,0,13l,7p1<ql>
<ep>
<m0>  This Dade County schools administrator stuck close to an education agenda. His take-home bill (--) raising high-school graduation standards from a 1.5 grade-point average to a 2.0 (--) got mixed in with one of the controversial issues of the session. By the last night, it was loaded down with lots of education bills, including one allowing school prayer. Turner has long opposed prayer in public schools. He said as much in an impassioned speech that didn't have an effect on the conservative Senate. The bill passed, prayer included. Most of his other victories came on easy-to-pass plans, like one naming State Road 112 for the late Dewey Knight Jr. Once, he showed he could muscle through a tough bill. He pushed a $250,000 claims bill for a man who was falsely arrested and had aggravated an old neck injury in a Dade jail cell (--) where he slept on the floor for a week. Senators killed the plan, 17-18. But Turner worked the room until he persuaded them to vote again. When they did, he'd changed enough minds that it passed on a 20-16 vote.<ql>
